# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-61970-cim
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] The **Common Information Model** (**CIM**) is an electric power transmission and distribution standard developed by the electric power industry.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] It aims to allow application software to exchange information about an electrical network.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] It has been officially adopted by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] The CIM is currently maintained as a UML model.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] It defines a common vocabulary and basic ontology.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] CIM models the network itself using the 'wires model'.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] It describes the basic components used to transport electricity.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] Measurements of power are modeled by another class.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] These measurements support the management of power flow at the transmission level, and by extension, the modeling of power through a revenue meter on the distribution network.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] The CIM can be used to derive 'design artifacts' (e.g.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] XML or RDF Schemas) as needed for the integration of related application software.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] CIM is also used to derive messages for the wholesale energy market with the framework for energy market communications, IEC 62325.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] The European style market profile is a profile derivation based on the CIM, intending to harmonize energy market data exchanges in Europe.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] ENTSO-E is a major contributor to the European style market profile.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] The core packages of the CIM are defined in IEC 61970-301, with a focus on the needs of electricity transmission, where related applications include energy management system, SCADA, and planning and optimization.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] IEC 61970-501 and 61970-452 define an XML format for network model exchanges using RDF.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] As of December 2024, there are proposals to extend CIM to cover reticulated gas networks.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] CIM and Substation Configuration Language (SCL) are developed in parallel under different IEC TC 57 working groups.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] Applications may use these standards to improve interoperability and data exchange by transforming SCL models into CIM models.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] Without harmonization, system and application development and implementation require engineering and design that applies to only one implementation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] Harmonization can be done by mixing the equipment topological approach of CIM and the functionality approach of SCL.
[src:iec-61970-cim/common-information-model-electricity] IEC TC 57 WG19 is involved in the harmonization CIM & SCL.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] An **electric power system** is a network of electrical components deployed to supply, transfer, and use electric power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] An example of a power system is the electrical grid that provides power to homes and industries within an extended area.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The electrical grid can be broadly divided into the generators that supply the power, the transmission system that carries the power from the generating centers to the load centers, and the distribution system that feeds the power to nearby homes and industries.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Smaller power systems are also found in industry, hospitals, commercial buildings, and homes.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A single line diagram helps to represent this whole system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The majority of these systems rely upon three-phase AC power—the standard for large-scale power transmission and distribution across the modern world.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Specialized power systems that do not always rely upon three-phase AC power are found in aircraft, electric rail systems, ocean liners, submarines, and automobiles.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1889, two electricians built the world's first power system at Godalming in England.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] It was powered by two water wheels and produced an alternating current that in turn supplied seven Siemens arc lamps at 250 volts and 34 incandescent lamps at 40 volts.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] However, supply to the lamps was intermittent and in 1882 Thomas Edison and his company, Edison Electric Light Company, developed the first steam-powered electric power station on Pearl Street in New York City.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The Pearl Street Station initially powered around 3,000 lamps for 59 customers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The power station generated direct current and operated at a single voltage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Direct current power could not be transformed easily or efficiently to the higher voltages necessary to minimize power loss during long-distance transmission, so the maximum economic distance between the generators and load was limited to around half a mile (800 m).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] That same year in London, Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs demonstrated the "secondary generator"—the first transformer suitable for use in a real power system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The practical value of Gaulard and Gibbs' transformer was demonstrated in 1884 at Turin where the transformer was used to light up 40 kilometers (25 miles) of railway from a single alternating current generator.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Despite the success of the system, the pair made some fundamental mistakes.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Perhaps the most serious was connecting the primaries of the transformers in series so that active lamps would affect the brightness of other lamps further down the line.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1885, Ottó Titusz Bláthy working with Károly Zipernowsky and Miksa Déri perfected the secondary generator of Gaulard and Gibbs, providing it with a closed iron core and its present name: the "transformer".
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The system lit more than 1000 carbon filament lamps and operated successfully from May until November of that year.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Also in 1885 George Westinghouse, an American entrepreneur, obtained the patent rights to the Gaulard-Gibbs transformer and imported a number of them along with a Siemens generator, and set his engineers to experimenting with them in hopes of improving them for use in a commercial power system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Using this knowledge he built a multi-voltage transformer-based alternating-current power system serving multiple homes and businesses at Great Barrington, Massachusetts in 1886.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The system was unreliable and short-lived, though, due primarily to generation issues.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] However, based on that system, Westinghouse would begin installing AC transformer systems in competition with the Edison Company later that year.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1888, Westinghouse licensed Nikola Tesla's patents for a polyphase AC induction motor and transformer designs.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Tesla consulted for a year at the Westinghouse Electric & Manufacturing Company but it took a further four years for Westinghouse engineers to develop a workable polyphase motor and transmission system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] By 1889, the electric power industry was flourishing, and power companies had built thousands of power systems (both direct and alternating current) in the United States and Europe.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These networks were effectively dedicated to providing electric lighting.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] During this time the rivalry between Thomas Edison and George Westinghouse's companies had grown into a propaganda campaign over which form of transmission (direct or alternating current) was superior, a series of events known as the "war of the currents".
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1891, Westinghouse installed the first major power system that was designed to drive a 100 horsepower (75 kW) synchronous electric motor, as well as provide electric lighting, at Telluride, Colorado.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In the United States the AC/DC competition came to an end when Edison General Electric was taken over by their chief AC rival, the Thomson-Houston Electric Company, forming General Electric.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1895, after a protracted decision-making process, alternating current was chosen as the transmission standard with Westinghouse building the Adams No.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] 1 generating station at Niagara Falls and General Electric building the three-phase alternating current power system to supply Buffalo at 11 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Developments in power systems continued beyond the nineteenth century.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1936 the first experimental high voltage direct current (HVDC) line using mercury arc valves was built between Schenectady and Mechanicville, New York.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] HVDC had previously been achieved by series-connected direct current generators and motors (the Thury system) although this suffered from serious reliability issues.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The first solid-state metal diode suitable for general power uses was developed by Ernst Presser at TeKaDe in 1928.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] It consisted of a layer of selenium applied on an aluminum plate.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1957, a General Electric research group developed the first thyristor suitable for use in power applications, starting a revolution in power electronics.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In that same year, Siemens demonstrated a solid-state rectifier, but it was not until the early 1970s that solid-state devices became the standard in HVDC, when GE emerged as one of the top suppliers of thyristor-based HVDC.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In 1979, a European consortium including Siemens, Brown Boveri & Cie and AEG realized the record HVDC link from Cabora Bassa to Johannesburg, extending more than 1,420 kilometers (880 miles) that carried 1.9 GW at 533 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In recent times, many important developments have come from extending innovations in the information and communications technology (ICT) field to the power engineering field.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For example, the development of computers meant load flow studies could be run more efficiently, allowing for much better planning of power systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Advances in information technology and telecommunication also allowed for effective remote control of a power system's switchgear and generators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Electric power is the product of two quantities: current and voltage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These two quantities can vary with respect to time (AC power) or can be kept at constant levels (DC power).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Most refrigerators, air conditioners, pumps and industrial machinery use AC power, whereas most computers and digital equipment use DC power (digital devices plugged into the mains typically have an internal or external power adapter to convert from AC to DC power).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] AC power has the advantage of being easy to transform between voltages and is able to be generated and utilised by brushless machinery.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] DC power remains the only practical choice in digital systems and can be more economical to transmit over long distances at very high voltages (see HVDC).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The ability to easily transform the voltage of AC power is important for two reasons: firstly, power can be transmitted over long distances with less loss at higher voltages.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] So in power systems where generation is distant from the load, it is desirable to step-up (increase) the voltage of power at the generation point and then step-down (decrease) the voltage near the load.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Secondly, it is often more economical to install turbines that produce higher voltages than would be used by most appliances, so the ability to easily transform voltages means this mismatch between voltages can be easily managed.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Solid-state devices, which are products of the semiconductor revolution, make it possible to transform DC power to different voltages, build brushless DC machines and convert between AC and DC power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Nevertheless, devices utilising solid-state technology are often more expensive than their traditional counterparts, so AC power remains in widespread use.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] All power systems have one or more sources of power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For some power systems, the source of power is external to the system but for others, it is part of the system itself—it is these internal power sources that are discussed in the remainder of this section.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Direct current power can be supplied by batteries, fuel cells or photovoltaic cells.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Alternating current power is typically supplied by a rotor that spins in a magnetic field in a device known as a turbo generator.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] There have been a wide range of techniques used to spin a turbine's rotor, from steam heated using fossil fuel (including coal, gas and oil) or nuclear energy to falling water (hydroelectric power) and wind (wind power).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The speed at which the rotor spins in combination with the number of generator poles determines the frequency of the alternating current produced by the generator.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] All generators on a single synchronous system, for example, the national grid, rotate at sub-multiples of the same speed and so generate electric current at the same frequency.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] If the load on the system increases, the generators will require more torque to spin at that speed and, in a steam power station, more steam must be supplied to the turbines driving them.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Thus the steam used and the fuel expended directly relate to the quantity of electrical energy supplied.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] An exception exists for generators incorporating power electronics such as gearless wind turbines or linked to a grid through an asynchronous tie such as a HVDC link — these can operate at frequencies independent of the power system frequency.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Depending on how the poles are fed, alternating current generators can produce a variable number of phases of power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A higher number of phases leads to more efficient power system operation but also increases the infrastructure requirements of the system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Electricity grid systems connect multiple generators operating at the same frequency: the most common being three-phase at 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] There are a range of design considerations for power supplies.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These range from the obvious: How much power should the generator be able to supply?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] What is an acceptable length of time for starting the generator (some generators can take hours to start)?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Is the availability of the power source acceptable (some renewables are only available when the sun is shining or the wind is blowing)?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] To the more technical: How should the generator start (some turbines act like a motor to bring themselves up to speed in which case they need an appropriate starting circuit)?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] What is the mechanical speed of operation for the turbine and consequently what are the number of poles required?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] What type of generator is suitable (synchronous or asynchronous) and what type of rotor (squirrel-cage rotor, wound rotor, salient pole rotor or cylindrical rotor)?
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power systems deliver energy to loads that perform a function.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These loads range from household appliances to industrial machinery.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Most loads expect a certain voltage and, for alternating current devices, a certain frequency and number of phases.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The appliances found in residential settings, for example, will typically be single-phase operating at 50 or 60 Hz with a voltage between 110 and 260 volts (depending on national standards).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] An exception exists for larger centralized air conditioning systems as these are now often three-phase because this allows them to operate more efficiently.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] All electrical appliances also have a wattage rating, which specifies the amount of power the device consumes.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] At any one time, the net amount of power consumed by the loads on a power system must equal the net amount of power produced by the supplies less the power lost in transmission.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Making sure that the voltage, frequency and amount of power supplied to the loads is in line with expectations is one of the great challenges of power system engineering.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A final consideration with loads has to do with power quality.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In addition to sustained overvoltages and undervoltages (voltage regulation issues) as well as sustained deviations from the system frequency (frequency regulation issues), power system loads can be adversely affected by a range of temporal issues.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These include voltage sags, dips and swells, transient overvoltages, flicker, high-frequency noise, phase imbalance and poor power factor.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power quality issues occur when the power supply to a load deviates from the ideal.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power quality issues can be especially important when it comes to specialist industrial machinery or hospital equipment.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Conductors carry power from the generators to the load.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Choice of conductors is based on considerations such as cost, transmission losses and other desirable characteristics of the metal like tensile strength.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Copper, with lower resistivity than aluminum, was once the conductor of choice for most power systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] However, aluminum has a lower cost for the same current carrying capacity and is now often the conductor of choice.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Overhead line conductors may be reinforced with steel or aluminium alloys.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Conductors in exterior power systems may be placed overhead or underground.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Overhead conductors are usually air insulated and supported on porcelain, glass or polymer insulators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Cables used for underground transmission or building wiring are insulated with cross-linked polyethylene or other flexible insulation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Conductors are often stranded for to make them more flexible and therefore easier to install.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Conductors are typically rated for the maximum current that they can carry at a given temperature rise over ambient conditions.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] As current flow increases through a conductor it heats up.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For insulated conductors, the rating is determined by the insulation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For bare conductors, the rating is determined by the point at which the sag of the conductors would become unacceptable.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The majority of the load in a typical AC power system is inductive; the current lags behind the voltage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Since the voltage and current are out-of-phase, this leads to the emergence of reactive power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Reactive power does no measurable work but is transmitted back and forth between the reactive power source and load every cycle.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Reactors consume reactive power and are used to regulate voltage on long transmission lines.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In light load conditions, where the loading on transmission lines is well below the surge impedance loading, the efficiency of the power system may actually be improved by switching in reactors.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Reactors installed in series in a power system also limit rushes of current flow, small reactors are therefore almost always installed in series with capacitors to limit the current rush associated with switching in a capacitor.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Series reactors can also be used to limit fault currents.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Capacitors and reactors are switched by circuit breakers, which results in sizeable step changes of reactive power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A solution to this comes in the form of synchronous condensers, static VAR compensators and static synchronous compensators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Briefly, synchronous condensers are synchronous motors that spin freely to generate or absorb reactive power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Static VAR compensators work by switching in capacitors using thyristors as opposed to circuit breakers allowing capacitors to be switched-in and switched-out within a single cycle.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] This provides a far more refined response than circuit-breaker-switched capacitors.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Static synchronous compensators take this a step further by achieving reactive power adjustments using only power electronics.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power electronics are semiconductor based devices that are able to switch quantities of power ranging from a few hundred watts to several hundred megawatts.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Despite their relatively simple function, their speed of operation (typically in the order of nanoseconds) means they are capable of a wide range of tasks that would be difficult or impossible with conventional technology.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The classic function of power electronics is rectification, or the conversion of AC-to-DC power, power electronics are therefore found in almost every digital device that is supplied from an AC source either as an adapter that plugs into the wall (see photo) or as component internal to the device.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] High-powered power electronics can also be used to convert AC power to DC power for long distance transmission in a system known as HVDC.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] HVDC is used because it proves to be more economical than similar high voltage AC systems for very long distances (hundreds to thousands of kilometres).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] HVDC is also desirable for interconnects because it allows frequency independence thus improving system stability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power electronics are also essential for any power source that is required to produce an AC output but that by its nature produces a DC output.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] They are therefore used by photovoltaic installations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power electronics are also found in practically all modern petrol-powered vehicles, this is because the power provided by the car's batteries alone is insufficient to provide ignition, air-conditioning, internal lighting, radio and dashboard displays for the life of the car.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] So the batteries must be recharged while driving—a feat that is typically accomplished using power electronics.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Some electric railway systems also use DC power and thus make use of power electronics to feed grid power to the locomotives and often for speed control of the locomotive's motor.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In the middle twentieth century, rectifier locomotives were popular, these used power electronics to convert AC power from the railway network for use by a DC motor.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Today most electric locomotives are supplied with AC power and run using AC motors, but still use power electronics to provide suitable motor control.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The use of power electronics to assist with the motor control and with starter circuits, in addition to rectification, is responsible for power electronics appearing in a wide range of industrial machinery.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power electronics even appear in modern residential air conditioners allow are at the heart of the variable speed wind turbine.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power systems contain protective devices to prevent injury or damage during failures.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The quintessential protective device is the fuse.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] When the current through a fuse exceeds a certain threshold, the fuse element melts, producing an arc across the resulting gap that is then extinguished, interrupting the circuit.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Given that fuses can be built as the weak point of a system, fuses are ideal for protecting circuitry from damage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Fuses however have two problems: First, after they have functioned, fuses must be replaced as they cannot be reset.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] This can prove inconvenient if the fuse is at a remote site or a spare fuse is not on hand.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] And second, fuses are typically inadequate as the sole safety device in most power systems as they allow current flows well in excess of that that would prove lethal to a human or animal.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The first problem is resolved by the use of circuit breakers—devices that can be reset after they have broken current flow.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In modern systems that use less than about 10 kW, miniature circuit breakers are typically used.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These devices combine the mechanism that initiates the trip (by sensing excess current) as well as the mechanism that breaks the current flow in a single unit.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Some miniature circuit breakers operate solely on the basis of electromagnetism.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In these miniature circuit breakers, the current is run through a solenoid, and, in the event of excess current flow, the magnetic pull of the solenoid is sufficient to force open the circuit breaker's contacts (often indirectly through a tripping mechanism).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In higher powered applications, the protective relays that detect a fault and initiate a trip are separate from the circuit breaker.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Early relays worked based upon electromagnetic principles similar to those mentioned in the previous paragraph, modern relays are application-specific computers that determine whether to trip based upon readings from the power system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Different relays will initiate trips depending upon different protection schemes.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For example, an overcurrent relay might initiate a trip if the current on any phase exceeds a certain threshold whereas a set of differential relays might initiate a trip if the sum of currents between them indicates there may be current leaking to earth.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The circuit breakers in higher powered applications are different too.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Air is typically no longer sufficient to quench the arc that forms when the contacts are forced open so a variety of techniques are used.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] One of the most popular techniques is to keep the chamber enclosing the contacts flooded with sulfur hexafluoride (SF6)—a non-toxic gas with sound arc-quenching properties.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Other techniques are discussed in the reference.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The second problem, the inadequacy of fuses to act as the sole safety device in most power systems, is probably best resolved by the use of residual-current devices (RCDs).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In any properly functioning electrical appliance, the current flowing into the appliance on the active line should equal the current flowing out of the appliance on the neutral line.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A residual current device works by monitoring the active and neutral lines and tripping the active line if it notices a difference.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Residual current devices require a separate neutral line for each phase and to be able to trip within a time frame before harm occurs.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Even with the installation of an RCD, exposure to electricity can still prove fatal.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In large electric power systems, supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is used for tasks such as switching on generators, controlling generator output and switching in or out system elements for maintenance.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The first supervisory control systems implemented consisted of a panel of lamps and switches at a central console near the controlled plant.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The lamps provided feedback on the state of the plant (the data acquisition function) and the switches allowed adjustments to the plant to be made (the supervisory control function).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Today, SCADA systems are much more sophisticated and, due to advances in communication systems, the consoles controlling the plant no longer need to be near the plant itself.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Instead, it is now common for plants to be controlled with equipment similar (if not identical) to a desktop computer.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The ability to control such plants through computers has increased the need for security—there have already been reports of cyber-attacks on such systems causing significant disruptions to power systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Despite their common components, power systems vary widely both with respect to their design and how they operate.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] This section introduces some common power system types and briefly explains their operation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Residential dwellings almost always take supply from the low voltage distribution lines or cables that run past the dwelling.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These operate at voltages of between 110 and 260 volts (phase-to-earth) depending upon national standards.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] A few decades ago small dwellings would be fed a single phase using a dedicated two-core service cable (one core for the active phase and one core for the neutral return).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The active line would then be run through a main isolating switch in the fuse box and then split into one or more circuits to feed lighting and appliances inside the house.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] By convention, the lighting and appliance circuits are kept separate so the failure of an appliance does not leave the dwelling's occupants in the dark.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] All circuits would be fused with an appropriate fuse based upon the wire size used for that circuit.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Circuits would have both an active and neutral wire with both the lighting and power sockets being connected in parallel.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Sockets would also be provided with a protective earth.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] This would be made available to appliances to connect to any metallic casing.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] If this casing were to become live, the theory is the connection to earth would cause an RCD or fuse to trip—thus preventing the future electrocution of an occupant handling the appliance.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Earthing systems vary between regions, but in countries such as the United Kingdom and Australia both the protective earth and neutral line would be earthed together near the fuse box before the main isolating switch and the neutral earthed once again back at the distribution transformer.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] There have been a number of minor changes over the years to practice of residential wiring.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Commercial power systems such as shopping centers or high-rise buildings are larger in scale than residential systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Electrical designs for larger commercial systems are usually studied for load flow, short-circuit fault levels and voltage drop.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The objectives of the studies are to assure proper equipment and conductor sizing, and to coordinate protective devices so that minimal disruption is caused when a fault is cleared.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Large commercial installations will have an orderly system of sub-panels, separate from the main distribution board to allow for better system protection and more efficient electrical installation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Typically one of the largest appliances connected to a commercial power system in hot climates is the HVAC unit, and ensuring this unit is adequately supplied is an important consideration in commercial power systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Regulations for commercial establishments place other requirements on commercial systems that are not placed on residential systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] For example, in Australia, commercial systems must comply with AS 2293, the standard for emergency lighting, which requires emergency lighting be maintained for at least 90 minutes in the event of loss of mains supply.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In the United States, the National Electrical Code requires commercial systems to be built with at least one 20 A sign outlet in order to light outdoor signage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Building code regulations may place special requirements on the electrical system for emergency lighting, evacuation, emergency power, smoke control and fire protection.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Power system management varies depending upon the power system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Residential power systems and even automotive electrical systems are often run-to-fail.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In aviation, the power system uses redundancy to ensure availability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] On the Boeing 747-400 any of the four engines can provide power and circuit breakers are checked as part of power-up (a tripped circuit breaker indicating a fault).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Larger power systems require active management.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In industrial plants or mining sites a single team might be responsible for fault management, augmentation and maintenance.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Where as for the electric grid, management is divided amongst several specialised teams.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Fault management involves monitoring the behaviour of the power system so as to identify and correct issues that affect the system's reliability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Fault management can be specific and reactive: for example, dispatching a team to restring conductor that has been brought down during a storm.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Or, alternatively, can focus on systemic improvements: such as the installation of reclosers on sections of the system that are subject to frequent temporary disruptions (as might be caused by vegetation, lightning or wildlife).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In addition to fault management, power systems may require maintenance or augmentation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] As often it is neither economical nor practical for large parts of the system to be offline during this work, power systems are built with many switches.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] These switches allow the part of the system being worked on to be isolated while the rest of the system remains live.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] At high voltages, there are two switches of note: isolators and circuit breakers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Circuit breakers are load-breaking switches where as operating isolators under load would lead to unacceptable and dangerous arcing.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] In a typical planned outage, several circuit breakers are tripped to allow the isolators to be switched before the circuit breakers are again closed to reroute power around the isolated area.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] This allows work to be completed on the isolated area.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Beyond fault management and maintenance one of the main difficulties in power systems is that the active power consumed plus losses must equal the active power produced.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] If load is reduced while generation inputs remain constant the synchronous generators will spin faster and the system frequency will rise.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] The opposite occurs if load is increased.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] As such the system frequency must be actively managed primarily through switching on and off dispatchable loads and generation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electric-power-system] Making sure the frequency is constant is usually the task of a system operator.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] An **electrical grid** (or **electricity network**) is an interconnected network for electricity delivery from producers to consumers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electrical grids consist of power stations, electrical substations to step voltage up or down, electric power transmission to carry power over long distances, and finally electric power distribution to customers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In that last step, voltage is stepped down again to the required service voltage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Power stations are typically built close to energy sources and far from densely populated areas.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electrical grids vary in size and can cover whole countries or continents.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] From small to large there are microgrids, wide area synchronous grids, and super grids.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The combined transmission and distribution network is part of electricity delivery, known as the *power grid*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Grids are nearly always synchronous, meaning all distribution areas operate with three phase alternating current (AC) frequencies synchronized (so that voltage swings occur at almost the same time).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This allows transmission of AC power throughout the area, connecting the electricity generators with consumers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Grids can enable more efficient electricity markets.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Although electrical grids are widespread, as of 2016, 1.4 billion people worldwide were not connected to an electricity grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] As electrification increases, the number of people with access to grid electricity is growing.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] About 840 million people (mostly in Africa), which is ca.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] 11% of the World's population, had no access to grid electricity in 2017, down from 1.2 billion in 2010.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electrical grids can be prone to malicious intrusion or attack; thus, there is a need for electric grid security.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Also as electric grids modernize and introduce computer technology, cyber threats start to become a security risk.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Particular concerns relate to the more complex computer systems needed to manage grids.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A microgrid is a local grid that is usually part of the regional wide-area synchronous grid, but which can disconnect and operate autonomously.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] It might do this in times when the main grid is affected by outages.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This is known as islanding, and it might run indefinitely on its own resources.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Compared to larger grids, microgrids typically use a lower voltage distribution network and distributed generators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Microgrids may not only be more resilient, but may be cheaper to implement in isolated areas.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A design goal is that a local area produces all of the energy it uses.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A *wide area synchronous grid* (also called an "interconnection" in North America) is an electrical grid at a regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For example, there are four major interconnections in North America (the Western Interconnection, the Eastern Interconnection, the Quebec Interconnection and the Texas Interconnection).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In Europe, one large grid connects most of Western Europe.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] These are also known as synchronous zones, the largest of which is the synchronous grid of Continental Europe (ENTSO-E) with 667 gigawatts (GW) of generation, and the widest region served being that of the IPS/UPS system serving countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity market trading across wide areas.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the ENTSO-E in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Each of the interconnects in North America are run at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] One disadvantage of a wide-area synchronous grid is that problems in one part can have repercussions across the whole grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For example, in 2018, Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a dispute with Serbia, leading to the phase across the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This caused certain kinds of clocks to become six minutes slow.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A *super grid* or *supergrid* is a wide-area transmission network that is intended to make possible the trade of high volumes of electricity across great distances.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] It is sometimes also referred to as a *mega grid*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Super grids can support a global energy transition by smoothing local fluctuations of wind energy and solar energy.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In this context, they are considered as a key technology to mitigate global warming.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Super grids typically use high-voltage direct current (HVDC) to transmit electricity long distances.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The latest generation of HVDC power lines can transmit energy with losses of only 1.6% per 1000 km.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electric utilities between regions are many times interconnected for improved economy and reliability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electrical interconnectors allow for economies of scale, allowing energy to be purchased from large, efficient sources.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Utilities can draw power from generator reserves from a different region to ensure continuing, reliable power and diversify their loads.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Interconnection also allows regions to have access to cheap bulk energy by receiving power from different sources.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For example, one region may be producing cheap hydro power during high water seasons, but in low water seasons, another area may be producing cheaper power through wind, allowing both regions to access cheaper energy sources from one another during different times of the year.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Neighboring utilities also help others to maintain the overall system frequency and also help manage tie transfers between utility regions.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electricity Interconnection Level (EIL) of a grid is the ratio of the total interconnector power to the grid divided by the installed production capacity of the grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Within the EU, it has set a target of national grids reaching 10% by 2020, and 15% by 2030.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electricity generation is the process of generating electric power at power stations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This is done ultimately from sources of primary energy typically with electromechanical generators driven by heat engines from fossil, nuclear, and geothermal sources, or driven by the kinetic energy of water or wind.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Other power sources are photovoltaics driven by solar insolation, and grid batteries.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The sum of the power outputs of generators on the grid is the production of the grid, typically measured in gigawatts (GW).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electric power transmission is the bulk movement of electrical energy from a generating site, via a web of interconnected lines, to an electrical substation, from which is connected to the distribution system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This networked system of connections is distinct from the local wiring between high-voltage substations and customers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Transmission networks are built with redundant pathways to prevent a single point of failure.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In case of line failures this redundancy allows power to be simply rerouted while repairs are done.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Because the power is often generated far from where it is consumed, the transmission system can cover great distances.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For a given amount of power, transmission efficiency is greater at higher voltages and lower currents.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Therefore, voltages are stepped up at the generating station, and stepped down at local substations for distribution to customers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Three-phase, compared to single-phase, can deliver much more power for a given amount of wire, since the neutral and ground wires are shared.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Further, three-phase generators and motors are more efficient than their single-phase counterparts.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, for conventional conductors one of the main losses are resistive losses which are a square law on current, and depend on distance.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] High voltage AC transmission lines can lose 1–4% per hundred miles.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, high-voltage direct current can have half the losses of AC.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Over very long distances, these efficiencies can offset the additional cost of the required AC/DC converter stations at each end.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Substations may perform many different functions but usually transform voltage from low to high (step up) and from high to low (step down).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Between the generator and the final consumer, the voltage may be transformed several times.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Distribution is the final stage in the delivery of power; it carries electricity from the transmission system to individual consumers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Substations connect to the transmission system and lower the transmission voltage to medium voltage ranging between 2 kV and 35 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] But the voltage levels varies very much between different countries, in Sweden medium voltage are normally 10 kV between 20 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Primary distribution lines carry this medium voltage power to distribution transformers located near the customer's premises.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Distribution transformers again lower the voltage to the utilization voltage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Customers demanding a much larger amount of power may be connected directly to the primary distribution level or the subtransmission level.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Distribution networks are divided into two types, radial or network.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In cities and towns of North America, the grid tends to follow the classic *radially fed* design.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A substation receives its power from the transmission network, the power is stepped down with a transformer and sent to a bus from which feeders fan out in all directions across the countryside.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] These feeders carry three-phase power, and tend to follow the major streets near the substation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] As the distance from the substation grows, the fanout continues as smaller laterals spread out to cover areas missed by the feeders.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This tree-like structure grows outward from the substation, but for reliability reasons, usually contains at least one unused backup connection to a nearby substation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This connection can be enabled in case of an emergency, so that a portion of a substation's service territory can be alternatively fed by another substation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] As of 2020, the largest form of grid energy storage is dammed hydroelectricity, with both conventional hydroelectric generation as well as pumped storage hydroelectricity.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Developments in battery storage have enabled commercially viable projects to store energy during peak production and release during peak demand, and for use when production unexpectedly falls giving time for slower responding resources to be brought online.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Two alternatives to grid storage are the use of peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps and demand response to shift load to other times.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The demand, or load on an electrical grid is the total electrical power being removed by the users of the grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The graph of the demand over time is called the *demand curve*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Baseload is the minimum load on the grid over any given period, peak demand is the maximum load.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Historically, baseload was commonly met by equipment that was relatively cheap to run, that ran continuously for weeks or months at a time, but globally this is becoming less common.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The extra peak demand requirements are sometimes produced by expensive peaking plants that are generators optimised to come on-line quickly but these too are becoming less common.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, if the demand of electricity exceeds the capacity of a local power grid, it will cause safety issues like burning out.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Grids are designed to supply electricity to their customers at largely constant voltages.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This has to be achieved with varying demand, variable reactive loads, and even nonlinear loads, with electricity provided by generators and distribution and transmission equipment that are not perfectly reliable.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Often grids use tap changers on transformers near to the consumers to adjust the voltage and keep it within specification.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In a synchronous grid all the generators must run at the same frequency, and must stay very nearly in phase with each other and the grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid, because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque, maintaining almost constant rotation speed as loading changes.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Energy is stored in the immediate short term by the rotational kinetic energy of the generators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Although the speed is kept largely constant, small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and are used as a way of assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic generation control (AGC) systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Conversely, when the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency naturally slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] When generators have identical droop speed control settings it ensures that multiple parallel generators with the same settings share load in proportion to their rating.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In addition, there's often central control, which can change the parameters of the AGC systems over timescales of a minute or longer to further adjust the regional network flows and the operating frequency of the grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For timekeeping purposes, the nominal frequency will be allowed to vary in the short term, but is adjusted to prevent line-operated clocks from gaining or losing significant time over the course of a whole 24 hour period.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Neighbouring grids that are not directly connected are almost always out-of-phase with each other.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Instead, high-voltage direct current lines or variable-frequency transformers are used, which allow two out-of-phase synchronous grids to share power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The sum of the maximum power outputs (nameplate capacity) of the generators attached to an electrical grid might be considered to be the capacity of the grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, in practice, they are never run flat out simultaneously.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Typically, some generators are kept running at lower output powers (spinning reserve) to deal with failures as well as variation in demand.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In addition generators can be off-line for maintenance or other reasons, such as availability of energy inputs (fuel, water, wind, sun etc.) or pollution constraints.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Most grid codes specify that the load is shared between the generators in merit order according to their marginal cost (i.e. cheapest first) and sometimes their environmental impact.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Thus cheap electricity providers tend to be run flat out almost all the time, and the more expensive producers are only run when necessary.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A central authority is usually designated to facilitate communication and develop protocols to maintain a stable grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation gained binding powers in the United States in 2006, and has advisory powers in the applicable parts of Canada and Mexico.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The U.S. government has also designated National Interest Electric Transmission Corridors, where it believes transmission bottlenecks have developed.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Where multiple utilities own generators connected to one electrical grid power pools are often formed which have agreements about responsibilities.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Each grid may have a system operator that is responsible for day-to-day running of one or more grids.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Failures are usually associated with generators or power transmission lines tripping circuit breakers due to faults leading to a loss of generation capacity for customers, or excess demand.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] This will often cause the frequency to reduce, and the remaining generators will react and together attempt to stabilize above the minimum.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] If that is not possible then a number of scenarios can occur.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A large failure in one part of the grid—unless quickly compensated for—can cause current to re-route itself to flow from the remaining generators to consumers over transmission lines of insufficient capacity, causing further failures.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] One downside to a widely connected grid is thus the possibility of cascading failure and widespread power outage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A *brownout* is an intentional or unintentional drop in voltage in an electrical power supply system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The reduction lasts for minutes or hours, as opposed to short-term voltage sag (or dip).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The term brownout comes from the dimming experienced by incandescent lighting when the voltage sags.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A voltage reduction may be an effect of disruption of an electrical grid, or may occasionally be imposed in an effort to reduce load and prevent a power outage, known as a blackout.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A *power outage* (also called a *power cut*, a *power out*, a *power blackout*, *power failure* or a *blackout*) is a loss of the electric power to a particular area.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Power failures can be caused by faults at power stations, damage to electric transmission lines, substations or other parts of the distribution system, a short circuit, cascading failure, fuse or circuit breaker operation, and human error.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Power failures are particularly critical at sites where the environment and public safety are at risk.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Institutions such as hospitals, sewage treatment plants, mines, shelters and the like will usually have backup power sources such as standby generators, which will automatically start up when electrical power is lost.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Other critical systems, such as telecommunication, are also required to have emergency power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The battery room of a telephone exchange usually has arrays of lead–acid batteries for backup and also a socket for connecting a generator during extended periods of outage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electrical generation and transmission systems may not always meet peak demand requirements— the greatest amount of electricity required by all utility customers within a given region.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In these situations, overall demand must be lowered, either by turning off service to some devices or cutting back the supply voltage (brownouts), in order to prevent uncontrolled service disruptions such as power outages (widespread blackouts) or equipment damage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Utilities may impose load shedding on service areas via targeted blackouts, rolling blackouts or by agreements with specific high-use industrial consumers to turn off equipment at times of system-wide peak demand.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A *black start* is the process of restoring an electric power station or a part of an electric grid to operation without relying on the external electric power transmission network to recover from a total or partial shutdown.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Normally, the electric power used within the plant is provided from the station's own generators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] If all of the plant's main generators are shut down, station service power is provided by drawing power from the grid through the plant's transmission line.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, during a wide-area outage, off-site power from the grid is not available.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the absence of grid power, a so-called black start needs to be performed to bootstrap the power grid into operation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] To provide a black start, some power stations have small diesel generators, normally called the *black start diesel generator* (BSDG), which can be used to start larger generators (of several megawatts capacity), which in turn can be used to start the main power station generators.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Generating plants using steam turbines require station service power of up to 10% of their capacity for boiler feedwater pumps, boiler forced-draft combustion air blowers, and for fuel preparation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] It is uneconomical to provide such a large standby capacity at each station, so black-start power must be provided over designated tie lines from another station.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Often hydroelectric power plants are designated as the black-start sources to restore network interconnections.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] A hydroelectric station needs very little initial power to start (just enough to open the intake gates and provide excitation current to the generator field coils), and can put a large block of power on line very quickly to allow start-up of fossil-fuel or nuclear stations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Certain types of combustion turbine can be configured for black start, providing another option in places without suitable hydroelectric plants.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In 2017 a utility in Southern California has successfully demonstrated the use of a battery energy storage system to provide a black start, firing up a combined cycle gas turbine from an idle state.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Despite novel institutional arrangements and network designs, power delivery infrastructures is experiencing aging across the developed world.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Demand response is a grid management technique where retail or wholesale customers are requested or incentivised either electronically or manually to reduce their load.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Currently, transmission grid operators use demand response to request load reduction from major energy users such as industrial plants.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Technologies such as smart metering can encourage customers to use power when electricity is plentiful by allowing for variable pricing.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The smart grid is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Resistance to distributed generation among grid operators may encourage providers to leave the grid and instead distribute power to smaller geographies.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The Rocky Mountain Institute and other studies foresee widescale grid defection.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] However, grid defection may be less likely in places such as Germany that have greater power demands in the winter.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Early electric energy was produced near the device or service requiring that energy.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the 1880s, electricity competed with steam, hydraulics, and especially coal gas.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Coal gas was first produced on customer's premises but later evolved into gasification plants that enjoyed economies of scale.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the industrialized world, cities had networks of piped gas, used for lighting.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] But gas lamps produced poor light, wasted heat, made rooms hot and smoky, and gave off hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the 1880s electric lighting soon became advantageous compared to gas lighting.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Electric utility companies established central stations to take advantage of economies of scale and moved to centralized power generation, distribution, and system management.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] After the war of the currents was settled in favor of AC power, with long-distance power transmission it became possible to interconnect stations to balance the loads and improve load factors.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries have liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that have led to the separation of the electricity transmission business from the distribution business.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the United Kingdom, Charles Merz, of the Merz & McLellan consulting partnership, built the Neptune Bank Power Station near Newcastle upon Tyne in 1901, and by 1912 had developed into the largest integrated power system in Europe.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Merz was appointed head of a parliamentary committee and his findings led to the Williamson Report of 1918, which in turn created the Electricity (Supply) Act 1919.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The bill was the first step towards an integrated electricity system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In 1925 the Weir Committee recommended the creation of a "national gridiron" and so the Electricity (Supply) Act 1926 created the Central Electricity Board (CEB).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The CEB standardized the nation's electricity supply and established the first synchronized AC grid, running at 132 kilovolts and 50 hertz but initially operated as regional grids.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] After brief overnight interconnection in 1937 they permanently and officially joined in 1938 becoming the UK National Grid.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In France, electrification began in the 1900s, with 700 communes in 1919, and 36,528 in 1938.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] At the same time, these close networks began to interconnect: Paris in 1907 at 12 kV, the Pyrénées in 1923 at 150 kV, and finally almost all of the country interconnected by 1938 at 220 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In 1946, the grid was the world's most dense.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] That year the state nationalised the industry, by uniting the private companies as Électricité de France.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The frequency was standardised at 50 Hz, and the 225 kV network replaced 110 kV and 120 kV.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Since 1956, service voltage has been standardised at 220/380 V, replacing the previous 127/220 V.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] During the 1970s, the 400 kV network, the new European standard, was implemented.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Starting on May 29, 1986, the end user service voltage will progressively change to 230/400 V ±10%.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the United States in the 1920s, utilities formed joint-operations to share peak load coverage and backup power.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In 1934, with the passage of the Public Utility Holding Company Act (U.S.), electric utilities were recognized as public goods of importance and were given outlined restrictions and regulatory oversight of their operations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 1992 required transmission line owners to allow electric generation companies open access to their network and led to a restructuring of how the electric industry operated in an effort to create competition in power generation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] No longer were electric utilities built as vertical monopolies, where generation, transmission and distribution were handled by a single company.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] Now, the three stages could be split among various companies, in an effort to provide fair access to high voltage transmission.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 allowed incentives and loan guarantees for alternative energy production and advance innovative technologies that avoided greenhouse emissions.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In China, electrification began in the 1950s.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In August 1961, the electrification of the Baoji-Fengzhou section of the Baocheng Railway was completed and delivered for operation, becoming China's first electrified railway.
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] From 1958 to 1998, China's electrified railway reached 6,200 miles (10,000 kilometres).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] As of the end of 2017, this number has reached 54,000 miles (87,000 kilometres).
[src:iec-61970-cim/electrical-grid] In the current railway electrification system of China, State Grid Corporation of China—Archived 2021-12-21 at the Wayback Machine—is an important power supplier.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Types of interoperability include **syntactic interoperability**, where two systems can communicate with each other, and cross-domain interoperability, where multiple organizations work together and exchange information.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] If two or more systems use common data formats and communication protocols, then they are capable of communicating with each other, and they exhibit *syntactic interoperability*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] XML and SQL are examples of common data formats and protocols.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Low-level data formats also contribute to syntactic interoperability, ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Beyond the ability of two or more computer systems to exchange information, semantic interoperability is the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results as defined by the end users of both systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] To achieve semantic interoperability, both sides must refer to a common information exchange reference model.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The content of the information exchange requests are unambiguously defined: what is sent is the same as what is understood.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Cross-domain interoperability involves multiple social, organizational, political, legal entities working together for a common interest or information exchange.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability implies exchanges between a range of products, or similar products from several different vendors, or even between past and future revisions of the same product.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability may be developed *post-facto*, as a special measure between two products, while excluding the rest, by using open standards.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] When a vendor is forced to adapt its system to a dominant system that is not based on open standards, it is compatibility, not interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Open standards rely on a broadly consultative and inclusive group, including representatives from vendors, academics and others holding a stake in the development that discusses and debates the technical and economic merits, demerits and feasibility of a proposed common protocol.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] After the doubts and reservations of all members are addressed, the resulting common document is endorsed as a *common standard*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This document may be subsequently released to the public, and henceforth becomes an *open standard*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] It is usually published and is available freely or at a nominal cost to any and all comers, with *no further encumbrances*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The vendors' products compete on the quality of their implementation, user interface, ease of use, performance, price, and a host of other factors, while keeping the customer's data intact and transferable even if they choose to switch to another competing product for business reasons.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] However, while "open" is a necessary condition for an interoperabilty standard, it is not a sufficient condition.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] For example, the standard-setting processes for the Fortran, C, and C++ languages are open, with a broadly-inclusive consultative group.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] But the resulting standards are not interoperability standards.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The data itself may be encumbered, e.g., by patents or pricing, leading to a dependence of all competing solutions on the original vendor, and possibly leading to a revenue stream from the competitors' customers back to the original vendor.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This revenue stream is the result of the original product's market dominance and not a result of any innate superiority.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Alternatively, it can be argued that even open processes are subject to the weight of past implementations and imperfect past designs and that the power of the dominant vendor to unilaterally correct or improve the system and impose the changes to all users facilitates innovation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Lack of an open standard can also become problematic for the customers, as in the case of the original vendor's inability to fix a certain problem that is an artifact of technical limitations in the original product.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Speaking from an e-government perspective, interoperability refers to the collaboration ability of cross-border services for citizens, businesses and public administrations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Exchanging data can be a challenge due to language barriers, different specifications of formats, varieties of categorizations and other hindrances.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] If data is interpreted differently, collaboration is limited, takes longer and is inefficient.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] For instance, if a citizen of country A wants to purchase land in country B, the person will be asked to submit the proper address data.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Address data in both countries includes full name details, street name and number, as well as a postal code.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The order of the address details might vary.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In the same language, it is not an obstacle to order the provided address data, but across language barriers, it becomes difficult.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] If the language uses a different writing system it is almost impossible if no translation tools are available.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability is used by researchers in the context of urban flood risk management.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Cities and urban areas worldwide are expanding, which creates complex spaces with many interactions between the environment, infrastructure and people.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] To address this complexity and manage water in urban areas appropriately, a system of systems approach to water and flood control is necessary.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At the strategic level, interoperability is an enabler for coalition building.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] It facilitates meaningful contributions by coalition partners.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At this level, interoperability issues center on harmonizing world views, strategies, doctrines, and force structures.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability is an element of coalition willingness to work together over the long term to achieve and maintain shared interests against common threats.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability at the operational and tactical levels is where strategic interoperability and technological interoperability come together to help allies shape the environment, manage crises, and win wars.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The benefits of interoperability at the operational and tactical levels generally derive from the interchangeability of force elements and units.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] *Technological interoperability* reflects the interfaces between organizations and systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] It focuses on communications and computers but also involves the technical capabilities of systems and the resulting mission compatibility between the systems and data of coalition partners.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At the technological level, the benefits of interoperability come primarily from their impacts at the operational and tactical levels in terms of enhancing flexibility.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Because first responders need to be able to communicate during wide-scale emergencies, interoperability is an important issue for law enforcement, firefighting, emergency medical services, and other public health and safety departments.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] It has been a major area of investment and research over the last 12 years.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Widely disparate and incompatible hardware impedes the exchange of information between agencies.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Agencies' information systems, such as computer-aided dispatch systems and records management systems, functioned largely in isolation, in so-called *information islands*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Agencies tried to bridge this isolation with inefficient, stopgap methods while large agencies began implementing limited interoperable systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] These approaches were inadequate and, in the US, the lack of interoperability in the public safety realm became evident during the 9/11 attacks on the Pentagon and World Trade Center structures.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Further evidence of a lack of interoperability surfaced when agencies tackled the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In contrast to the overall national picture, some states, including Utah, have already made great strides forward.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The Utah Highway Patrol and other departments in Utah have created a statewide data sharing network.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The Commonwealth of Virginia is one of the leading states in the United States in improving interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The Interoperability Coordinator leverages a regional structure to better allocate grant funding around the Commonwealth so that all areas have an opportunity to improve communications interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The State of Washington seeks to enhance interoperability statewide.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Washington recognizes that collaborating on system design and development for wireless radio systems enables emergency responder agencies to efficiently provide additional services, increase interoperability, and reduce long-term costs.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This work saves the lives of emergency personnel and the citizens they serve.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The U.S. government is making an effort to overcome the nation's lack of public safety interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The Department of Homeland Security's Office for Interoperability and Compatibility (OIC) is pursuing the SAFECOM and CADIP and Project 25 programs, which are designed to help agencies as they integrate their CAD and other IT systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This project will partner the OIC with agencies in several locations, including Silicon Valley.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This program will use case studies to identify the best practices and challenges associated with linking CAD systems across jurisdictional boundaries.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] These lessons will create the tools and resources public safety agencies can use to build interoperable CAD systems and communicate across local, state, and federal boundaries.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Governance entities can increase interoperability through their legislative and executive powers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Conversely, government-mandated interoperability has been heavily criticized as leading to monopolies that become too big to fail.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] For example, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission's implementation of 1975 amendments to the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that were intended to ensure interoperability was blamed for driving all regional clearinghouses and depositories out of business in the United States.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] As a result, the National Securities Clearing Corporation is the sole clearinghouse; the Depository Trust Company is the sole repository; and their parent, the Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation, has enormous market power over central counterparty clearing in the United States.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In contrast, the federal government of the United States did not attempt to mandate or regulate credit card interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This allowed credit card networks to naturally develop interoperability (in the sense that almost every payment terminal can automatically accept almost every credit card), so that Visa Inc. was not left as the last credit card network standing.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Desktop interoperability is a subset of software interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In the early days, the focus of interoperability was to integrate web applications with other web applications.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Over time, open-system containers were developed to create a virtual desktop environment in which these applications could be registered and then communicate with each other using simple publish–subscribe patterns.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Rudimentary UI capabilities were also supported, allowing windows to be grouped with other windows.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Today, desktop interoperability has evolved into full-service platforms that include container support, basic exchange between web and web, but also native support for other application types and advanced window management.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The very latest interop platforms also include application services such as universal search, notifications, user permissions and preferences, 3rd party application connectors and language adapters for in-house applications.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Search interoperability refers to the ability of two or more information collections to be searched by a single query.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Specifically related to web-based search, the challenge of interoperability stems from the fact that designers of web resources typically have little or no need to concern themselves with exchanging information with other web resources.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Federated Search technology, which does not place format requirements on the data owner, has emerged as one solution to search interoperability challenges.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In addition, standards, such as Open Archives Initiative Protocol for Metadata Harvesting, Resource Description Framework, and SPARQL, have emerged that also help address the issue of search interoperability related to web resources.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Such standards also address broader topics of interoperability, such as allowing data mining.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] With respect to software, the term *interoperability* is used to describe the capability of different programs to exchange data via a common set of exchange formats, to read and write the same file formats, and to use the same communication protocols.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The lack of interoperability can be a consequence of a lack of attention to standardization during the design of a program.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Indeed, interoperability is not taken for granted in the non-standards-based portion of the computing world.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Standards-developing organizations provide open public software specifications to facilitate interoperability; examples include the Oasis-Open organization and buildingSMART (formerly the International Alliance for Interoperability).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Another example of a neutral party is the RFC documents from the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The Open Service for Lifecycle Collaboration community is working on finding a common standard in order that software tools can share and exchange data e.g., bugs, tasks, requirements etc.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The final goal is to agree on an open standard for interoperability of open source application lifecycle management tools.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Java is an example of an interoperable programming language that allows for programs to be written once and run anywhere with a Java virtual machine.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] A program in Java, so long as it does not use system-specific functionality, will maintain interoperability with all systems that have a Java virtual machine available.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Applications will maintain compatibility because, while the implementation is different, the underlying language interfaces are the same.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Product engineering Implements the common standard, or a sub-profile thereof, as defined by the industry and community partnerships with the specific intention of achieving interoperability with other software implementations, also following the same standard or sub-profile thereof.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Industry and community partnership Industry and community partnerships, either domestic or international, sponsor standard workgroups with the purpose of defining a common standard that may be used to allow software systems to intercommunicate for a defined purpose.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At times, an industry or community will sub-profile an existing standard produced by another organization to reduce options and thus make interoperability more achievable for implementations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] This technique has some of the same technical results as using a common vendor product to produce interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The common technology can come through third-party libraries or open-source developments.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Standard implementation Software interoperability requires a common agreement that is normally arrived at via an industrial, national or international standard.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Each of these has an important role in reducing variability in intercommunication software and enhancing a common understanding of the end goal to be achieved.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Language interoperability is the capability of two different programming languages to natively interact as part of the same system and operate on the same kind of data structures.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] There are many ways programming languages are interoperable with one another.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are interoperable as they are used in tandem in webpages.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Some object oriented languages are interoperable thanks to their shared hosting virtual machine (e.g. .NET CLI compliant languages in the Common Language Runtime and JVM compliant languages in the Java Virtual Machine).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Unified interoperability is the property of a system that allows for the integration of real-time and non-real time communications, activities, data, and information services (i.e., unified) and the display and coordination of those services across systems and devices (i.e., interoperability).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Unified interoperability provides the capability to communicate and exchange processing across different applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability tends to be regarded as an issue for experts and its implications for daily living are sometimes underrated.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The European Union Microsoft competition case shows how interoperability concerns important questions of power relationships.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In 2004, the European Commission found that Microsoft had abused its market power by deliberately restricting interoperability between Windows Workgroup servers and non-Microsoft work group servers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] By doing so, Microsoft was able to protect its dominant market position for work group server operating systems, the heart of corporate IT networks.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Microsoft was ordered to disclose complete and accurate interface documentation, which could enable rival vendors to compete on an equal footing (*the interoperability remedy*).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability has also surfaced in the software patent debate in the European Parliament (June–July 2005).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability is often more of an organizational issue.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability can have a significant impact on the organizations concerned, raising issues of ownership (do people want to share their data? or are they dealing with information silos?), labor relations (are people prepared to undergo training?) and usability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In this context, a more apt definition is captured in the term *business process interoperability*.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Interoperability can have important economic consequences; for example, research has estimated the cost of inadequate interoperability in the US capital facilities industry to be $15.8 billion a year.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] If competitors' products are not interoperable (due to causes such as patents, trade secrets or coordination failures), the result may well be monopoly or market failure.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] For this reason, it may be prudent for user communities or governments to take steps to encourage interoperability in various situations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At least 30 international bodies and countries have implemented eGovernment-based interoperability framework initiatives called e-GIF, while in the US, there is the NIEM initiative.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The need for *plug-and-play* interoperability – the ability to take a medical device out of its box and easily make it work with one's other devices – has attracted great attention from both healthcare providers and industry.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Increasingly, medical devices like incubators and imaging systems feature software that integrates at the point of care and with electronic systems, such as electronic medical records.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] At the 2016 Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society (RAPS) meeting, experts in the field like Angela N.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Johnson with GE Healthcare and Jeff Shuren of the United States Food and Drug Administration, provided practical seminars on how companies developing new medical devices, and hospitals installing them, can work more effectively to align interoperable software systems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Railways have greater or lesser interoperability depending on conforming to standards of gauge, couplings, brakes, signalling, loading gauge, and structure gauge to mention a few parameters.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] For passenger rail service, different railway platform height and width clearance standards may also affect interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] North American freight and intercity passenger railroads are highly interoperable, but systems in Europe, Asia, Africa, Central and South America, and Australia are much less so.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The parameter most difficult to overcome (at reasonable cost) is incompatibility of gauge, though variable gauge axle systems can be used on rolling stock.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The condition achieved among communications-electronics systems or items of communications-electronics equipment when information or services can be exchanged directly and satisfactorily between them or their users.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The degree of interoperability should be defined when referring to specific cases.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Many organizations are dedicated to interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Some concentrate on eGovernment, eBusiness or data exchange in general.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] Internationally, Network Centric Operations Industry Consortium facilitates global interoperability across borders, language and technical barriers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In the built environment, the International Alliance for Interoperability started in 1994 and was renamed buildingSMART in 2005.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In Europe, the European Commission and its IDABC program issue the European Interoperability Framework.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] IDABC was succeeded by the Interoperability Solutions for European Public Administrations (ISA) program.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] They also initiated the Semantic Interoperability Centre Europe (SEMIC.EU).
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] A European Land Information Service (EULIS) was established in 2006, as a consortium of European National Land Registers.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The aim of the service is to establish a single portal through which customers are provided with access to information about individual properties, about land and property registration services, and about the associated legal environment.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The European Interoperability Framework (EIF) considered four kinds of interoperability: legal interoperability, organizational interoperability, semantic interoperability, and technical interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In the European Research Cluster on the Internet of Things (IERC) and IoT Semantic Interoperability Best Practices; four kinds of interoperability are distinguished: syntactical interoperability, technical interoperability, semantic interoperability, and organizational interoperability.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] In the United States, the General Services Administration Component Organization and Registration Environment (CORE.GOV) initiative provided a collaboration environment for component development, sharing, registration, and reuse in the early 2000s.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] A related initiative is the ongoing National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) work and component repository.
[src:iec-61970-cim/interoperability] The National Institute of Standards and Technology serves as an agency for measurement standards.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The **Unified Modeling Language** (**UML**) is a general-purpose, object-oriented, visual modeling language that provides a way to visualize the architecture and design of a system, similar to the function of a blueprint.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML defines notation for 14 types of diagrams which focus on aspects such as behavior, interaction, and structure.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The UML has a metamodel defined by the OMG UML specification.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The metamodel defines the elements in an object-oriented model such as classes and properties.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] It is essentially the same thing as the metamodel in object-oriented programming (OOP), however for OOP, the metamodel is primarily used at run time to dynamically inspect and modify an application object model.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The UML metamodel provides a mathematical, formal foundation for the graphic views used in the modeling language to describe an emerging system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML was created in an attempt to define a standard language for object-oriented programming at the OOPSLA '95 Conference.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Originally, Grady Booch and James Rumbaugh merged their models into a unified model.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] This was followed by Booch's company Rational Software purchasing Ivar Jacobson's Objectory company and merging their model into the UML.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] At the time Rational and Objectory were two of the dominant players in the small world of independent vendors of object-oriented tools and methods.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The Object Management Group (OMG) then took ownership of UML.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The creation of UML was motivated by the desire to standardize the disparate nature of notational systems and approaches to software design at the time.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] In 1997, UML was adopted as a standard by the Object Management Group (OMG) and has been managed by this organization ever since.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] In 2005, UML was also published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as the **ISO/IEC 19501** standard.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Since then the standard has been periodically revised to cover the latest revision of UML.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Most developers do not use UML per se, but instead produce more informal diagrams, often hand-drawn.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] These diagrams, however, often include elements from UML.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML is primarily used for software development (in any industry or domain) but also used outside elsewhere including business processes, system functions, database schemas, workflow in the legal systems, medical electronics, Health care systems, and hardware design..
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The UML is used by the OMG itself to define other OMG products such as the Unified Architecture Framework (UAF) and the Systems Modelling Language (SysML) v1.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML is designed for use with many object-oriented software development methods, both today and for the methods when it was first developed – including OMT, Booch method, Objectory, and especially RUP, which it was originally intended to be used with when work began at Rational Software.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Although originally intended for object-oriented design documentation, UML has been used effectively in other contexts such as modeling business process.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] As UML is not inherently linked to a particular programming language, it can be used for modeling a system independent of language.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Some UML tools generate source code from a UML model.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] In addition to syntactical (notational) elements with well-defined semantics, UML diagrams also allow for free-form comments (notes) that explain aspects such as usage, constraints, and intents.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML models can be exchanged among UML tools via the XML Metadata Interchange (XMI) format.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] As with database Chen, Bachman, and ISO ER diagrams, class models are specified to use "look-across" cardinalities, even though several authors (Merise, Elmasri & Navathe, amongst others) prefer same-side or "look-here" for roles and both minimum and maximum cardinalities.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Recent researchers (Feinerer and Dullea et al.) have shown that the "look-across" technique used by UML and ER diagrams is less effective and less coherent when applied to *n*-ary relationships of order strictly greater than 2.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Feinerer says: "Problems arise if we operate under the look-across semantics as used for UML associations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] An artifact is the physical entity that is deployed to a node.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Other UML elements such as classes and components are first manifest into artifacts and instances of these artifacts are then deployed.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Artifacts can be composed of other artifacts.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The OMG developed a metamodeling architecture to define UML, called the Meta-Object Facility (MOF).
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] MOF is designed as a four-layered architecture, as shown in the image at right.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] It provides a meta-meta model at the top, called the M3 layer.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] This M3-model is the language used by Meta-Object Facility to build metamodels, called M2-models.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] An example of a Layer 2 Meta-Object Facility model is the UML metamodel, which describes the UML itself.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] These M2-models describe elements of the M1-layer, and thus M1-models.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] These would be, for example, models written in the UML.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] A software architecture description might describe runtime instances of the system..
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The last layer is the M0-layer - the real world thing being described or modelled.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The UML metamodel can be extended using a mechanism called stereotyping.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] This has been criticized as being insufficient/untenable by Brian Henderson-Sellers and Cesar Gonzalez-Perez in "Uses and Abuses of the Stereotype Mechanism in UML 1.x and 2.0".
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML 2 defines 14 types or kinds of diagrams – shown as a taxonomy in the image.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Structure diagrams emphasize the structure of the system – using objects, classifiers, relationships, attributes and operations.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] They are used to document software architecture.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Behavior diagrams emphasize the behavior of a system by showing collaborations among objects and changes to the internal states of objects.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] They are used to describe the functionality of a system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Interaction diagrams, a subset of behavior diagrams, emphasize the flow of control and data between components of a system.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] In 2013, UML had been marketed by OMG for many contexts, but aimed primarily at software development with limited success.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] It has been treated, at times, as a design silver bullet, which leads to problems.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML misuse includes overuse (designing every part of the system with it, which is unnecessary) and assuming that novices can design with it.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] It is considered a large language, with many constructs.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Some people (including Jacobson) feel that UML's size hinders learning and therefore uptake.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Visual Studio removed support for UML in 2016 due to lack of use.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML has evolved since the second half of the 1990s and has its roots in the object-oriented programming methods developed in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The image shows a timeline of the history of UML and other object-oriented modeling methods and notation.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Rational Software hired James Rumbaugh from General Electric in 1994 and after that, the company became the source for two of the most popular object-oriented modeling approaches of the day: Rumbaugh's object-modeling technique (OMT) and Grady Booch's method.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] They were soon assisted in their efforts by Ivar Jacobson, the creator of the object-oriented software engineering (OOSE) method, who joined them at Rational in 1995.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML is originally based on the notations of the Booch method, the object-modeling technique (OMT), and object-oriented software engineering (OOSE), which were integrated into a single language.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML was developed at Rational Software in 1994–1995, with further development led by them through 1996.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Under the technical leadership of Rumbaugh, Jacobson, and Booch, a consortium called the UML Partners was organized in 1996 to complete the *Unified Modeling Language (UML)* specification and propose it to the Object Management Group (OMG) for standardization.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The partnership also contained additional interested parties (for example HP, DEC, IBM, and Microsoft).
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The UML Partners' UML 1.0 draft was proposed to the OMG in January 1997 by the consortium.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] During the same month, the UML Partners formed a group, designed to define the exact meaning of language constructs, chaired by Cris Kobryn and administered by Ed Eykholt, to finalize the specification and integrate it with other standardization efforts.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The result of this work, UML 1.1, was submitted to the OMG in August 1997 and adopted by the OMG in November 1997.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] After the first release, a task force was formed to improve the language, which released several minor revisions, 1.3, 1.4, and 1.5.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The standards it produced (as well as the original standard) have been noted as being ambiguous and inconsistent.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML 2.0 major revision replaced version 1.5 in 2005, which was developed with an enlarged consortium to improve the language further to reflect new experiences on the usage of its features.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] Although UML 2.1 was never released as a formal specification, versions 2.1.1 and 2.1.2 appeared in 2007, followed by UML 2.2 in February 2009.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML 2.3 was formally released in May 2010.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML 2.4.1 was formally released in August 2011.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] UML 2.5 was released in October 2012 as an "In progress" version and was officially released in June 2015.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] The formal version 2.5.1 was adopted in December 2017.
[src:iec-61970-cim/unified-modeling-language] It continues to be updated and improved by the revision task force, who resolve any issues with the language.
